NAME
    head - output the first part of files

SYNOPSIS
    head [OPTION]... [FILE]...

DESCRIPTION
    Print the first 10 lines of each FILE to standard output. With more
    than one FILE, precede each output block with a header giving the
    file name. With no FILE, or when FILE is '-', read standard input.

OPTIONS
    -c N, --bytes=N
        Print the first N bytes of each file. If N is prefixed with '-',
        print all bytes except the last N bytes.

        N may have a suffix: b=512, kB=1000, K=1024, MB=1000*1000,
        M=1024*1024, GB, G, TB, T.

    -n N, --lines=N
        Print the first N lines (default: 10). If N is prefixed with
        '-', print all lines except the last N lines.

    -q, --quiet, --silent
        Never print file name headers.

    -v, --verbose
        Always print file name headers.

    -z, --zero-terminated
        Line delimiter is NUL, not newline.

    --version
        Output version information and exit.

    --help
        Display help and exit.

EXAMPLES
    head file.txt
        Print first 10 lines of file.txt.

    head -n 20 file.txt
        Print first 20 lines.

    head -c 100 file.bin
        Print first 100 bytes.

    head -n -5 file.txt
        Print all lines except the last 5.

    head -v file1.txt file2.txt
        Print first 10 lines of each file with headers.

    head -1 *.txt
        Print the first line of each .txt file.

EXIT STATUS
    0   Success.
    1   Error occurred.
